medicines. Weaving extensive historical research with insights from political economy and science and technology studies, Victor Roy demystifies an oft-missed dynamic in this debate: the reach of financialized capitalism into how medicines are made, priced, and valued. His account travels between public and private labs, Wall Street and corporate boardrooms, public health meetings and health centers to trace the ways sofosbuvir-based medicines became financial assets dominated by strategies of speculation and extraction at the expense of access and care. Provocative and sobering, this book illuminates the harmful impact of allowing financial markets to supersede democracy and human health and points to the necessary work of building more equitable futures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aDrug developmentxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aDrugsxPriceszUnited States. 0aHepatitis CxTreatmentxPriceszUnited States. 0aPharmaceutical industryxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aSofosbuvirxPriceszUnited States. 7aMEDICAL / Ethics.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520388727zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520388727zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520388727/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA  aZDB-23-UCY